<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
<pageBreakToken pageId="28" pageNumber="71" start="start">20</pageBreakToken>
. 
<taxonomicName LSID="218083BC-F45B-5CD5-9C40-89809D95FF4D" authority="(Mandl, 1981)" baseAuthorityName="Mandl" baseAuthorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cylindera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cylindera (Eugrapha) contorta subsp. valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="contorta" subGenus="Eugrapha" subSpecies="valdenbergi">Cylindera (Eugrapha) contorta (Fischer von Waldheim, 1828), ssp. valdenbergi (Mandl, 1981)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
In the southern Levant found exclusively in sandy shore habitats along the Mediterranean Sea. Larval development takes place a few centimeters above the mean sea level, just above where most of the waves break (
<bibRefCitation author="Valdenberg, A" journalOrPublisher="Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center" pageId="44" pageNumber="87" pagination="38 - 48" refId="B105" refString="Valdenberg, A, 1983. The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew). Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center 1: 38 - 48" title="The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew)." volume="1" year="1983">Valdenberg 1983</bibRefCitation>
), though larval holes are occasionally flooded by seawater. The nominate subspecies is found in both coastal and inland habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Cassola, F" journalOrPublisher="Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne" pageId="39" pageNumber="82" pagination="193 - 214" refId="B30" refString="Cassola, F, Jaskula, R, 2004. Materials to the knowledge of the tiger beetles of Romania (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae). Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne 73: 193 - 214" title="Materials to the knowledge of the tiger beetles of Romania (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae)." volume="73" year="2004">
Cassola and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="JaskuÅ‚a">Jaskula</normalizedToken>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
). Attracted by light (own observation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
Adults from the beginning of May until mid-November (
<bibRefCitation author="Valdenberg, A" journalOrPublisher="Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center" pageId="44" pageNumber="87" pagination="38 - 48" refId="B105" refString="Valdenberg, A, 1983. The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew). Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center 1: 38 - 48" title="The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew)." volume="1" year="1983">Valdenberg 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Few adults also from March onwards (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.578.7383" author="Matalin, AV" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="115 - 160" refId="B82" refString="Matalin, AV, Chikatunov, VI, 2016. The tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelinae) of Israel and adjacent lands. ZooKeys 578: 115 - 160, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.578.7383" title="The tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelinae) of Israel and adjacent lands." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.578.7383" volume="578" year="2016">Matalin and Chikatunov 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nussbaum, Y" journalOrPublisher="YES Quarterly" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="7 - 15" refId="B87" refString="Nussbaum, Y, 1987. Tiger beetles of Israel and Sinai (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae). YES Quarterly 4: 7 - 15" title="Tiger beetles of Israel and Sinai (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae)." volume="4" year="1987">Nussbaum 1987</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae overwinter mostly as second and third instars (and rarely also first instars). Egg laying begins immediately with the appearance of the adults in spring, and in certain years a few individuals may complete an entire life-cycle in the same summer, though most do not (
<bibRefCitation author="Valdenberg, A" journalOrPublisher="Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center" pageId="44" pageNumber="87" pagination="38 - 48" refId="B105" refString="Valdenberg, A, 1983. The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew). Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center 1: 38 - 48" title="The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew)." volume="1" year="1983">Valdenberg 1983</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Distribution range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
The nominate form is found from south-eastern Europe (Romania and Ukraine) and Asia Minor to Central Asia and China. The 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cephalota" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cephalota subsp. valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="contorta" subSpecies="valdenbergi">Cephalota subspecies valdenbergi</taxonomicName>
is patchily located in a small area along the Mediterranean coast from western Egypt to northern Israel (
<bibRefCitation author="Horn, W" journalOrPublisher="Bundesamt fuer Naturschutz, Bonn" pageId="42" pageNumber="85" refId="B61" refString="Horn, W, 1931. Zur Kenntnis der Cicindelen-Fauna von Cypern, Syrien, Sizilien, Aegypten und Sued-Griechenland (insbesondere der geographischen Verbreitung der Arten Cicindela aphrodisia Baudi, C. campestris suffriani Loew, C. contorta Fisch. und dorsata Br., sowie C. aulica Dej.). Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte Seance du 17 November: 157-163." title="Zur Kenntnis der Cicindelen-Fauna von Cypern, Syrien, Sizilien, Aegypten und Sued-Griechenland (insbesondere der geographischen Verbreitung der Arten Cicindela aphrodisia Baudi, C. campestris suffriani Loew, C. contorta Fisch. und dorsata Br., sowie C. aulica Dej.). Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte Seance du 17 November: 157 - 163." year="1931">Horn 1931</bibRefCitation>
, Mandl 1981). The nominate form does not occur along the Mediterranean coast (
<bibRefCitation author="Wiesner, J" journalOrPublisher="Erna Bauer, Keltern" pageId="45" pageNumber="88" refId="B114" refString="Wiesner, J, 1992. Checklist of the tiger beetles of the world. Erna Bauer, Keltern" title="Checklist of the tiger beetles of the world." year="1992">Wiesner 1992</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Distribution in the southern Levant.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
In Egypt around Abu Qir, Maadia and Ras el Bar (
<bibRefCitation author="Abdel-Dayem, MS" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin of the Entomological Society of Egypt" pageId="38" pageNumber="81" pagination="193 - 217" refId="B1" refString="Abdel-Dayem, MS, El-Haewagri, MSA, Yassan, SA, 2003. A review of the Egyptian species of tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelidae). Bulletin of the Entomological Society of Egypt 80: 193 - 217" title="A review of the Egyptian species of tiger beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, Cicindelidae)." volume="80" year="2003">Abdel-Dayem et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Alfieri, A" journalOrPublisher="Memoires de la Societe Entomologique de Egypte" pageId="38" pageNumber="81" pagination="1 - 361" refId="B5" refString="Alfieri, A, 1976. The Coleoptera of Egypt. Memoires de la Societe Entomologique de Egypte 5: 1 - 361" title="The Coleoptera of Egypt." volume="5" year="1976">Alfieri 1976</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Horn, W" journalOrPublisher="Bundesamt fuer Naturschutz, Bonn" pageId="42" pageNumber="85" refId="B61" refString="Horn, W, 1931. Zur Kenntnis der Cicindelen-Fauna von Cypern, Syrien, Sizilien, Aegypten und Sued-Griechenland (insbesondere der geographischen Verbreitung der Arten Cicindela aphrodisia Baudi, C. campestris suffriani Loew, C. contorta Fisch. und dorsata Br., sowie C. aulica Dej.). Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte Seance du 17 November: 157-163." title="Zur Kenntnis der Cicindelen-Fauna von Cypern, Syrien, Sizilien, Aegypten und Sued-Griechenland (insbesondere der geographischen Verbreitung der Arten Cicindela aphrodisia Baudi, C. campestris suffriani Loew, C. contorta Fisch. und dorsata Br., sowie C. aulica Dej.). Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte Seance du 17 November: 157 - 163." year="1931">Horn 1931</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mandl, K" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="167 - 182" refId="B80" refString="Mandl, K, 1981a. Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae). Entomologica Basiliensia 6: 167 - 182" title="Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae)." volume="6" year="1981 a">Mandl 1981a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Nussbaum, Y" journalOrPublisher="YES Quarterly" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="7 - 15" refId="B87" refString="Nussbaum, Y, 1987. Tiger beetles of Israel and Sinai (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae). YES Quarterly 4: 7 - 15" title="Tiger beetles of Israel and Sinai (Coleoptera: Cicindelidae)." volume="4" year="1987">Nussbaum 1987</bibRefCitation>
). In Israel from Bat Yam to Akko, though the Bat Yam population is thought to be extinct since several decades (
<bibRefCitation author="Valdenberg, A" journalOrPublisher="Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center" pageId="44" pageNumber="87" pagination="38 - 48" refId="B105" refString="Valdenberg, A, 1983. The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew). Shappirit - Journal of the Israel Entomology Center 1: 38 - 48" title="The tiger beetles family. General survey of the family and key to species in Israel and Sinai (in Hebrew)." volume="1" year="1983">Valdenberg 1983</bibRefCitation>
; own observation).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="71" type="taxonomic notes">
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Taxonomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="28" pageNumber="71">
<bibRefCitation author="Mandl, K" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="167 - 182" refId="B80" refString="Mandl, K, 1981a. Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae). Entomologica Basiliensia 6: 167 - 182" title="Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae)." volume="6" year="1981 a">Mandl (1981a)</bibRefCitation>
described the taxon 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cylindera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cylindera valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valdenbergi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Cylindera valdenbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Maâ€™agan">Ma'agan</normalizedToken>
Michael as a subspecies. It is characterized by the excessive pale elytral pattern (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29â€“32" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 29 - 32. Cylindera (sub-) species: 29 C. contorta s. str. (male) 30 C. rectangularis (female) 31 C. contorta valdenbergi (male) 32 C. contorta valdenbergi (female)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.734.21989.figures29-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/183617" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">31</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29â€“32" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 29 - 32. Cylindera (sub-) species: 29 C. contorta s. str. (male) 30 C. rectangularis (female) 31 C. contorta valdenbergi (male) 32 C. contorta valdenbergi (female)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.734.21989.figures29-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/183617" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">32</figureCitation>
), though there is some variation in the pattern between individuals. However, the pale elytral coloration differs even within the nominate form strongly. Some populations from the Caspian Sea show similar elytral pattern as 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cylindera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cylindera valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valdenbergi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Cylindera valdenbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mandl, K" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Basiliensia" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" pagination="167 - 182" refId="B80" refString="Mandl, K, 1981a. Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae). Entomologica Basiliensia 6: 167 - 182" title="Neue Coleopteren-Taxa vom Nahen bis zum Fernen Osten (Col. Cicindelidae, Carabidae und Chrysomelidae)." volume="6" year="1981 a">Mandl 1981a</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Werner, K" journalOrPublisher="Science Nat, Venette" pageId="44" pageNumber="87" refId="B110" refString="Werner, K, 1992. Cicindelidae 2. Science Nat, Venette" title="Cicindelidae 2." year="1992">Werner 1992</bibRefCitation>
). Mandl mentioned in his description small differences in the copulatory pieces of the median lobe of aedeagus. As we believe this character is still not sufficiently studied. But the material we studied let us assume that 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cylindera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cylindera valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valdenbergi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Cylindera valdenbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the nominate subspecies at least in the proportion and shape of the pronotum and the elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29â€“32" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 29 - 32. Cylindera (sub-) species: 29 C. contorta s. str. (male) 30 C. rectangularis (female) 31 C. contorta valdenbergi (male) 32 C. contorta valdenbergi (female)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.734.21989.figures29-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/183617" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">29</figureCitation>
). We recommend conducting a detailed study, including morphometric and molecular methods, to clarify the status of both taxa. 
<bibRefCitation author="Ptashkovsky, Y" journalOrPublisher="Cornell University Press, Ithaca and London" pageId="43" pageNumber="86" refId="B93" refString="Ptashkovsky, Y, 2013. Beetles of Israel. self-published, Tel Aviv." title="Beetles of Israel. self-published, Tel Aviv." year="2013">Ptashkovsky (2013)</bibRefCitation>
includes a photograph of &quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Lophyra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lophyra contorta subsp. valdenbergi" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="contorta" subSpecies="valdenbergi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Lophyra contorta valdenbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot;, but the shown specimen belongs to the nominate subspecies of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fischer von Waldheim" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Cicindelidae" genus="Cylindera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cylindera contorta" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="71" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="contorta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">Cylindera contorta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(cf. Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 29â€“32" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 29 - 32. Cylindera (sub-) species: 29 C. contorta s. str. (male) 30 C. rectangularis (female) 31 C. contorta valdenbergi (male) 32 C. contorta valdenbergi (female)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.734.21989.figures29-32" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/183617" pageId="28" pageNumber="71">29</figureCitation>
), and with all probability the photographed specimen was not collected in Israel.
</paragraph>
